To further confirm whether CDs exist in the outer shell of nanocomposites, powder X-ray diffraction (XRD) and Fourier-transform infrared (FT-IR) were conducted. The observed diffraction peaks in the XRD patterns (Fig. 2
                        ) can be entirely indexed to the NiFe2O4 nanoparticles [20]. Moreover, the XRD patterns of NiFeC displays diffraction peaks around at 2θ=23° corresponding to EDTA-2Na derived CDs [24]. FT-IR spectra of CDs, NiFeC (Fig. S3) display characteristic peaks of CDs at 3200–3550cm−1, 1610cm−1 and 1437cm−1 corresponding to OH, CO and amide CN stretching vibration, respectively [27]. It can be easily found that the FT-IR spectrum of NiFeC possesses all characteristic peaks of CDs, but these bonds cannot be found in that of NiFe2O4 except the bond assigned to OH stretching vibration. These aboundant oxygen-containing functional groups of the CDs could contribute to the high adsorption competence of NiFeC toward TC. The bonds from 1350 to 1470cm−1 are assigned to CH2
                         stretching vibration deformation of CDs [28]. The results fully indicate the existence of CDs on the surface of NiFeC, indicating the formation of NiFe2O4-CDs nanocomposites.
